          "body": "The chapter's pastoral heart is verses 8-16. The pivot at verse 8 is grammatically abrupt — 'But you, Israel, My servant' — and the contrast is the chapter's main point. The nations scramble to manufacture security; Israel is addressed by name, called 'My servant,' 'My chosen,' 'the descendant of Abraham My friend' (41:8). The threefold divine title in verse 8 sets up the fivefold divine promise in verse 10: I am with you / I am your God / I will strengthen you / I will help you / I will uphold you. These are not divine feelings about Israel — they are divine commitment verbs in the first person. John Oswalt observes that the 'do not fear' command (41:10, 13, 14) is grounded not in Israel's strength or circumstances but in the unchanging character of the God who speaks. The nadir is verse 14's address: 'you worm Jacob, you men of Israel.' *Tola* — worm — is not metaphor for meanness of character but for smallness, weakness, and helplessness. Precisely that helpless creature is the object of the Holy One's redeeming love. The chapter's transformation is not from bad to good but from nothing to everything — the worm becomes a threshing sledge (41:15), the scattered chaff is replaced by mountains pulverized for Israel's winnowing (41:16), and the end is worship: 'you will rejoice in the LORD, you will glory in the Holy One of Israel' (41:16)."
