        "excerpt": "'He fastens it with nails, so that it will not totter.'",
        "body": "Verses 5-7 are parenthetical in the chapter's argument but essential to its pastoral point. After the LORD's self-identification in verse 4, we expect the nations to repent or believe. Instead they flee to the workshop. The coastlands see and are afraid (41:5), the ends of the earth tremble (41:5), they draw near and come together — not to seek God but to reassure one another and manufacture idols. The mutual encouragement ('Be strong!' in 41:6) is a bitter parody of the divine promise to Israel ('I will strengthen you,' *amats*, in 41:10).\n\nThe workshop scene in verse 7 is one of Isaiah's most pointed satires. Craftsmen encouraging one another, smiths cheering smiths, the finished solder declared 'good' (*tov*) — the language deliberately echoes Genesis 1's divine declaration that creation is 'good.' But the craftsmen's 'good' must be bolted down: 'He fastens it with nails so that it will not totter.' An idol that requires human engineering to remain vertical is not a god; it is a problem. The very activity meant to secure divine protection reveals the absence of any such protection.\n\nTim Keller (in his exposition of the idol texts of Isaiah) notes that the idol-making process in these verses is a precise description of how all idolatry works: we take something from the created order (metal, wood, relationship, money, power), invest it with the function of security and ultimacy, and then expend enormous energy maintaining its stability — because it cannot maintain itself. The nails are the tell. Every idol requires human maintenance. The living God requires none; He sustains His own purposes and upholds the arm that trusts Him (41:10).\n\nThe irony of *chazaq* (the word for 'nailing down' in 41:7 and for God's upholding grip in 41:13) should not be missed. The nations *chazaq* their idols; the LORD *chazaq*s Israel. The nations must grip their gods; Israel's God grips them. This word-level contrast is precisely the pastoral argument Isaiah is making: the question is not 'which religion?' but 'which direction does the strength flow?'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chazaq* appears four times in the chapter (41:7 ×2, 9, 13), carrying the meaning from human reinforcement of idols to divine upholding of Israel. The root means to grip, to hold firm, to strengthen — the same action describes idol maintenance and divine covenant faithfulness."
